    "summary": "The Somali Civil War began with the overthrow of President Siad Barre's military government in January 1991 following years of clan-based armed opposition. The collapse of the central government plunged Somalia into a multi-faction conflict that would persist for decades. The country fragmented along clan lines as competing warlords vied for control of Mogadishu and regional territories. The war produced one of the worst humanitarian catastrophes of the post-Cold War period: widespread famine in 1991–1992 killed an estimated 300,000 people, prompting an international humanitarian intervention.\n\nThe United States led a military intervention under UN authorization in December 1992 to secure humanitarian relief deliveries. The mission evolved toward attempting to neutralize the most powerful warlord, General Mohamed Farah Aidid, which led to the [[event:3680|Battle of Mogadishu]] in October 1993 — the Black Hawk Down incident — in which eighteen American soldiers were killed. The United States subsequently withdrew its forces, and the broader UN mission ended in 1995, leaving Somalia without effective central government.\n\nThe absence of a functioning state created conditions exploited by extremist groups. The Islamic Courts Union briefly controlled much of southern Somalia in 2006 before being ousted by Ethiopian intervention. Al-Shabaab, an Islamist militant group, subsequently became the primary armed challenger to the internationally recognized government. Somalia's experience of state failure has been widely studied as a case of the challenges of state collapse and reconstruction.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Somali_Civil_War",
